WEBVTT

00:00:01.602 --> 00:00:02.936
-Our next guest is an Emmy
nominated actress and producer

00:00:02.936 --> 00:00:04.571
you know from her work
in "WandaVision"

00:00:04.571 --> 00:00:06.273
and the Marvel
Cinematic Universe,

00:00:06.273 --> 00:00:08.308
as well as films such
as "Wind River,"

00:00:08.308 --> 00:00:10.444
"Ingrid Goes West,"
and "His Three Daughters."

00:00:10.444 --> 00:00:12.513
She stars in "Eternity,"
which is in theaters

00:00:12.513 --> 00:00:13.981
everywhere this Thanksgiving.

00:00:13.981 --> 00:00:15.249
Let's take a look.

00:00:16.250 --> 00:00:19.453
-How's it looking?
-[ Panting ]

00:00:19.453 --> 00:00:22.256
So, what?
What am I supposed to do?

00:00:23.390 --> 00:00:26.226
I need you to tell me
what to do.

00:00:26.226 --> 00:00:28.228
-Oh, my dear. Okay.

00:00:28.228 --> 00:00:32.165
I read your file and you are
smart, passionate and decisive.

00:00:32.165 --> 00:00:34.268
-Oh, I am?

00:00:34.268 --> 00:00:37.070
-I have complete faith
that you will choose

00:00:37.070 --> 00:00:39.306
the right eternity
and the right person

00:00:39.306 --> 00:00:40.707
to spend it with.

00:00:40.707 --> 00:00:42.609
-[ Moans ]
-You'll do.

00:00:42.643 --> 00:00:46.013
-Do for what?
[ Knock on door ]

00:00:46.013 --> 00:00:47.648
-Were you expecting
someone or...?

00:00:47.648 --> 00:00:48.949
-Please welcome back
to the show

00:00:48.949 --> 00:00:51.251
our friend Elizabeth Olsen,
everybody.

00:00:51.251 --> 00:00:55.122
[ Cheers and applause ]

00:00:55.122 --> 00:01:04.164
♪♪

00:01:04.164 --> 00:01:10.370
♪♪

00:01:10.370 --> 00:01:12.439
Hi.
-Have you ever worn

00:01:12.439 --> 00:01:14.141
tights with your heels, Seth?

00:01:14.141 --> 00:01:16.810
-I haven't, but based on
how you were moving,

00:01:16.810 --> 00:01:18.212
it might not be that easy.
-It was hard.

00:01:18.212 --> 00:01:19.479
-Yeah.
-It's already hard.

00:01:19.479 --> 00:01:21.415
-I don't know why
I just did that to myself.

00:01:21.415 --> 00:01:24.852
It was so scary walking
from there to here.

00:01:24.852 --> 00:01:27.588
-You had a real fear
in your eyes.

00:01:27.588 --> 00:01:29.823
-[ Laughs ]
-Like, you were looking at me

00:01:29.823 --> 00:01:31.758
like you had, like,
had brief amnesia

00:01:31.758 --> 00:01:34.494
and didn't realize who I was
or what this was.

00:01:34.494 --> 00:01:35.762
-I was lost.

00:01:35.762 --> 00:01:37.664
-Yes.
-Completely lost.

00:01:37.664 --> 00:01:39.867
-I do -- I mostly because
I don't want anybody to do it.

00:01:39.867 --> 00:01:42.169
If someone like
pulled the fire alarm right now,

00:01:42.169 --> 00:01:44.705
you would be the last one out
of here by a full 10 minutes.

00:01:44.705 --> 00:01:46.440
-Well, I would take these off,

00:01:46.440 --> 00:01:47.841
and then I'd be sliding
all over this floor.

00:01:47.841 --> 00:01:49.610
-So you'd lose either way.

00:01:49.610 --> 00:01:51.545
-I would, I mean,
also, I'm very restrict--

00:01:51.545 --> 00:01:53.447
This is fine, we're good.
We're having a good time.

00:01:53.447 --> 00:01:54.948
-Yeah!
-[ Laughs ]

00:01:54.948 --> 00:01:56.884
[ Cheers and applause ]

00:01:56.884 --> 00:02:00.921
-I, um, let me offer you
a brief congratulations.

00:02:00.921 --> 00:02:02.789
I saw you on my friend
"Jimmy Kimmel Show"

00:02:02.789 --> 00:02:04.958
talking about how happy you are
about the Dodgers

00:02:04.958 --> 00:02:06.393
in their World Series victory.
-Yeah.

00:02:06.393 --> 00:02:07.895
-Congratulations.
-Well, I didn't do anything

00:02:07.895 --> 00:02:10.163
but thank you on their behalf.
-You're very welcome, yes.

00:02:10.163 --> 00:02:12.499
-Um, how great are --
were those series?

00:02:12.499 --> 00:02:14.201
-Well,
it was an amazing series.

00:02:14.201 --> 00:02:16.370
Now, this is the
truly amazing thing to me

00:02:16.370 --> 00:02:18.172
is you kind of came to Dodgers

00:02:18.172 --> 00:02:20.073
fandom sort of
in the last 10 years.

00:02:20.073 --> 00:02:21.708
Is that accurate?
-That's correct. That's correct.

00:02:21.708 --> 00:02:23.210
-And they're the
only sports team you care about.

00:02:23.210 --> 00:02:24.545
-That's correct.
-Wow.

00:02:24.545 --> 00:02:25.913
-Yeah.
-You're like a person

00:02:25.913 --> 00:02:29.116
who's like, "I only like gold."

00:02:29.116 --> 00:02:31.185
-I do only like gold.
-Yeah, you have one thing.

00:02:31.185 --> 00:02:34.821
-I only like gold.
You can have your diamonds.

00:02:34.821 --> 00:02:37.324
You can have your silver,
I only like gold

00:02:37.324 --> 00:02:38.458
and the Dodgers.

00:02:38.458 --> 00:02:39.826
-I would love --
I think I can get you

00:02:39.826 --> 00:02:42.296
a cable news ad,
just like you're talking about

00:02:42.296 --> 00:02:43.931
gold during commercial breaks.
-[ Laughs ]

00:02:43.931 --> 00:02:46.533
-Um, did you go to any
of the games?

00:02:46.533 --> 00:02:48.468
-Well, I do.
I go to -- I did.

00:02:48.468 --> 00:02:50.537
I -- I went to a postseason game

00:02:50.537 --> 00:02:53.407
and I was reminded why I should
never go to a postseason game.

00:02:53.407 --> 00:02:54.508
-Yeah.
-Every time I've gone to

00:02:54.508 --> 00:02:55.576
a postseason game,
they -- they lose.

00:02:55.576 --> 00:02:57.444
-Yeah.
-Um, they -- I went to the

00:02:57.444 --> 00:02:58.579
Brewers where they lost.

00:02:58.579 --> 00:03:03.584
And I also watched them lose to,
uh, the Red Sox

00:03:03.584 --> 00:03:05.552
when they lost in 2000,
I think -- what was that?

00:03:05.552 --> 00:03:07.254
'18 or '19?
-Yeah, 18.

00:03:07.254 --> 00:03:09.089
-Yeah.
So I was there when --

00:03:09.089 --> 00:03:10.791
I was at the Dodger Stadium
when -- when...

00:03:10.791 --> 00:03:12.159
-I think, by the way,
I did the same.

00:03:12.159 --> 00:03:14.795
So I am a Red Sox fan.
And in 2004 I had been to --

00:03:14.795 --> 00:03:16.964
[ Cheers and applause ]
Thank you. Thank you, everybody.

00:03:16.964 --> 00:03:19.399
Um, see?
I accept congratulations.

00:03:19.399 --> 00:03:22.202
-Well, a belated congratulations
on the one I watched to win.

00:03:22.202 --> 00:03:23.670
-Thank you very much.
Yeah, yeah, thank you.

00:03:23.670 --> 00:03:24.972
Thanks for everything
you did that night.

00:03:24.972 --> 00:03:26.039
-[ Laughs ]
-Well, we saw you there.

00:03:26.039 --> 00:03:28.475
We were like, "We got a shot."
-Yeah.

00:03:28.475 --> 00:03:30.110
-But I had only gone to games

00:03:30.110 --> 00:03:31.612
where the Red Sox
had lost to the Yankees.

00:03:31.612 --> 00:03:33.013
I think I had gone to, like,
three in a row,

00:03:33.013 --> 00:03:34.748
and I had tickets
to the famous game 4

00:03:34.748 --> 00:03:36.850
American League
Championship Series,

00:03:36.850 --> 00:03:38.652
and I gave the tickets away
because I'm like,

00:03:38.652 --> 00:03:40.254
I'm the problem.
-Right.

00:03:40.254 --> 00:03:42.289
-And then we won
the next eight games,

00:03:42.289 --> 00:03:44.925
and no one has given
me a plaque yet.

00:03:44.925 --> 00:03:46.760
-Right.
And it is because of you.

00:03:46.760 --> 00:03:48.195
-Of course it's because of me.
-Yeah.

00:03:48.195 --> 00:03:49.563
I mean, I would -- I would agree
with that.

00:03:49.563 --> 00:03:51.031
-Thank you.
-I just know I shouldn't

00:03:51.031 --> 00:03:52.165
be going to these
post game series.

00:03:52.165 --> 00:03:53.367
-Also, can we say
something else?

00:03:53.367 --> 00:03:54.668
A lot of those games
were on too late,

00:03:54.668 --> 00:03:57.838
and, uh, we have to get to bed.

00:03:57.838 --> 00:03:59.473
-I'm watching West coast time.

00:03:59.473 --> 00:04:00.774
-Oh, that's right.
-Yeah, so I'm okay.

00:04:00.774 --> 00:04:03.443
-This is -- I will say,
this World Series

00:04:03.443 --> 00:04:05.646
for East coasters was brutal.
-It was brutal.

00:04:05.646 --> 00:04:08.582
And I also do like the two hours
of the post game show

00:04:08.582 --> 00:04:10.384
that follows
because I have Spectrum,

00:04:10.384 --> 00:04:12.553
and so they do like
a whole separate thing.

00:04:12.553 --> 00:04:15.622
Like, you change the channel
from Fox to Fox Sports

00:04:15.622 --> 00:04:17.024
whatever it is,
one or something,

00:04:17.024 --> 00:04:18.559
and then you go to Spectrum.

00:04:18.559 --> 00:04:21.595
-So you actually like watching
post game analysis?

00:04:21.595 --> 00:04:23.130
-Yes.
-Wow.

00:04:23.130 --> 00:04:24.531
-Well, specifically
for Spectrum,

00:04:24.531 --> 00:04:26.166
there's a guy named
David Vassegh

00:04:26.166 --> 00:04:29.236
who interviews the guys,
and he's kind --

00:04:29.236 --> 00:04:31.138
they like -- I can't tell
if they're bullying him.

00:04:31.138 --> 00:04:33.874
-Okay.
-Uh, but he's very funny,

00:04:33.874 --> 00:04:36.009
But I don't know what's --
I don't actually know

00:04:36.009 --> 00:04:37.744
what their relationship is to
him, I can't tell.

00:04:37.744 --> 00:04:40.013
-So you're watching it less
about sports and more about,

00:04:40.013 --> 00:04:41.448
like, the human dynamics
at play?

00:04:41.448 --> 00:04:43.116
-Yes. That's why I can't
get into football,

00:04:43.116 --> 00:04:44.985
because they all have,
you know, guards on their face.

00:04:44.985 --> 00:04:47.221
-Oh, you, for you,
if you can't see the face,

00:04:47.221 --> 00:04:48.989
no interest.
-I'm --Yeah.

00:04:48.989 --> 00:04:50.057
I'm invested in the characters.

00:04:50.057 --> 00:04:52.559
-Okay, great.
-Yeah.

00:04:52.559 --> 00:04:54.528
[ Laughs ]

00:04:54.528 --> 00:04:56.496
-I want to talk about
your movie.

00:04:56.496 --> 00:04:57.898
-"Eternity" is what it's called.
-I'm sorry, "Eternity."

00:04:57.898 --> 00:04:59.900
-Yes, yes.
-But it's sort of --

00:04:59.900 --> 00:05:02.269
I've heard it billed
as a fantasy rom com.

00:05:02.269 --> 00:05:03.871
Do you feel
like that's accurate?

00:05:03.871 --> 00:05:06.006
-Yeah, it's a rom com
in the afterlife.

00:05:06.006 --> 00:05:08.275
So it depends.
Is the afterlife a fantasy?

00:05:08.275 --> 00:05:09.710
-Yeah.
I was happy to see it.

00:05:09.710 --> 00:05:11.445
I think in this day and age,

00:05:11.445 --> 00:05:12.980
I like seeing --
I really enjoy --

00:05:12.980 --> 00:05:16.783
I felt nice knowing that there's
like a -- an afterlife.

00:05:16.783 --> 00:05:18.385
I was like,
"Oh, I'd be good with this one."

00:05:18.385 --> 00:05:20.487
-You like this one?
-Yeah. Because you know why?

00:05:20.487 --> 00:05:22.189
There's immediately red tape
bull [bleep].

00:05:22.189 --> 00:05:24.625
-Yes.
There's a lot of red tape.

00:05:24.625 --> 00:05:26.627
And you like it.
-I would be happy about that.

00:05:26.627 --> 00:05:28.095
I'd be like, "Oh, good, it's
not going to be that different."

00:05:28.095 --> 00:05:29.530
-No, it's very bureaucratic.

00:05:29.530 --> 00:05:31.398
It's very similar
to the culture we have today.

00:05:31.398 --> 00:05:32.499
-Yeah.
-We're just throwing

00:05:32.499 --> 00:05:34.835
consumerism at people.
-Yeah.

00:05:34.835 --> 00:05:37.804
-It's like -- it's definitely
like a capitalist afterlife.

00:05:37.804 --> 00:05:39.773
-And you immediately, like,
show up in the afterlife

00:05:39.773 --> 00:05:41.842
and have to do the thing
none of us ever want to do,

00:05:41.842 --> 00:05:43.243
which is make a decision.

00:05:43.243 --> 00:05:45.345
-Yes, and everyone's forced
to make a decision very quickly

00:05:45.345 --> 00:05:47.147
for a week, for eternity,
for the rest of their lives.

00:05:47.147 --> 00:05:48.649
-And they can't change it,
and they're stuck with it.

00:05:48.649 --> 00:05:51.151
-Yes, and there's -- there's
nothing else they can do.

00:05:51.151 --> 00:05:53.253
-You have a --
I've heard you say

00:05:53.253 --> 00:05:55.088
this is a dream role for you.
-Yeah.

00:05:55.088 --> 00:05:57.624
-But there's a very
specific reason that it's true.

00:05:57.624 --> 00:06:00.761
-Yes, because I play a
90-year-old woman who dies

00:06:00.761 --> 00:06:02.696
and wakes up in the afterlife
in this body.

00:06:02.696 --> 00:06:04.131
-Yeah.
-And, you know, usually when

00:06:04.131 --> 00:06:06.033
people do romantic comedies,

00:06:06.033 --> 00:06:09.469
they're supposed to be,
I think, sexually attractive.

00:06:09.469 --> 00:06:11.471
And there's something
really nice about --

00:06:11.471 --> 00:06:14.575
-Not for me.
That's not right.

00:06:14.575 --> 00:06:16.476
I don't believe love has
anything to do with that.

00:06:16.476 --> 00:06:19.246
-[ Laughs ] Yeah, you're not
interested in that.

00:06:19.246 --> 00:06:20.848
-I actually had --
I paid to have

00:06:20.848 --> 00:06:22.649
some actors remake
"Pretty Woman"

00:06:22.649 --> 00:06:24.885
all 90-year-olds.

00:06:24.885 --> 00:06:26.820
-But how interesting
would that be?

00:06:26.820 --> 00:06:29.089
-It was very --
I'll give you the VHS.

00:06:29.089 --> 00:06:31.291
[ Laughter ]

00:06:31.291 --> 00:06:32.860
-Oh, that's when you made it.

00:06:32.860 --> 00:06:34.728
-Yeah, yeah, yeah.
-Um, yeah.

00:06:34.728 --> 00:06:36.864
So, I mean, there was
something really different

00:06:36.864 --> 00:06:39.967
to get to lean into,
and I do feel like an old lady.

00:06:39.967 --> 00:06:41.902
-In real life.
-Yeah.

00:06:41.902 --> 00:06:43.504
-Old soul.
-Not like wise.

00:06:43.504 --> 00:06:46.573
I do just feel like a little
out of touch with the times.

00:06:46.573 --> 00:06:48.075
-Okay.
Have you always felt this way?

00:06:48.075 --> 00:06:49.576
-Yeah.
-Okay.

00:06:49.576 --> 00:06:51.178
So even in college,
you feel like

00:06:51.178 --> 00:06:53.881
your friends would be like,
"Oh, she's out of touch

00:06:53.881 --> 00:06:55.516
with the times."
-Yes.

00:06:55.516 --> 00:06:56.650
I don't really know
what's going on in culture.

00:06:56.650 --> 00:06:57.684
-Gotcha.
-Yeah.

00:06:57.684 --> 00:06:59.720
Um, but I do know about 67.

00:06:59.720 --> 00:07:02.089
-Oh, congrats

00:07:02.089 --> 00:07:04.057
Congratulations.
-I think -- Thank you.

00:07:04.057 --> 00:07:05.659
I'm really into 67.

00:07:05.659 --> 00:07:06.994
-Interesting.
-Yeah.

00:07:06.994 --> 00:07:08.862
-Now I have children who say it.
-Yeah.

00:07:08.862 --> 00:07:10.931
-And I've made
an active choice to --

00:07:10.931 --> 00:07:13.967
to ask no follow ups.
-Okay.

00:07:13.967 --> 00:07:15.235
I can explain it to you.

00:07:15.235 --> 00:07:16.703
-Do you want to try?
-Yeah.

00:07:16.703 --> 00:07:17.871
I think this is
on the explain it now.

00:07:17.871 --> 00:07:20.174
-This is on the record now,
so just FYI.

00:07:20.174 --> 00:07:21.942
-So I think the reason
they love it

00:07:21.942 --> 00:07:23.810
is because
it's absurd and random.

00:07:23.810 --> 00:07:25.712
-Yeah.
-And how great.

00:07:25.712 --> 00:07:27.247
-Yeah.
-Like, I think we're really

00:07:27.247 --> 00:07:29.917
doing a lot of things that are,
uh, I don't know,

00:07:29.917 --> 00:07:32.719
maybe cynical or pointing --
pointing at something.

00:07:32.719 --> 00:07:35.389
And there's something
really funny to me about the,

00:07:35.389 --> 00:07:39.893
like, abstraction and absurdity
of just getting excited

00:07:39.893 --> 00:07:42.663
about two numbers
that are in order.

00:07:42.663 --> 00:07:45.199
-Yeah. That there in order
is even crazier.

00:07:45.199 --> 00:07:46.200
It's like -- like,
they're not like

00:07:46.200 --> 00:07:47.901
no one's ever six then seven.

00:07:47.901 --> 00:07:49.570
You're like,
that's all they've done.

00:07:49.570 --> 00:07:51.205
-Yeah.
It's -- It's not --

00:07:51.205 --> 00:07:52.940
it's not like
a funny combination.

00:07:52.940 --> 00:07:54.141
-No.
-It's just like how

00:07:54.141 --> 00:07:55.943
it's always been.
-It's really great.

00:07:55.943 --> 00:07:59.413
But I feel like the gift I'm
giving my sons is to, like,

00:07:59.413 --> 00:08:01.748
just be, like,
dumbfounded by it.

00:08:01.748 --> 00:08:03.483
-Right.
-Cause, like, I think also

00:08:03.483 --> 00:08:05.118
their joy is, like,
I don't get it.

00:08:05.118 --> 00:08:07.187
-Right.
That's what they love.

00:08:07.187 --> 00:08:08.555
-So I'm always like,
"What is this?"

00:08:08.555 --> 00:08:10.457
And they're like, "[ Laughs ]"
-Right.

00:08:10.457 --> 00:08:11.992
And there's nothing to say.

00:08:11.992 --> 00:08:13.694
-Yeah, there's nothing to say.
They can't explain.

00:08:13.694 --> 00:08:16.296
-Except watching someone else
be so dumbfounded.

00:08:16.296 --> 00:08:18.699
-Yeah, which is the joy.
I'm very --

00:08:18.699 --> 00:08:21.268
I'm growing into my role as
we talk about being old souls,

00:08:21.268 --> 00:08:23.670
which is like my role right now
is to be in a house

00:08:23.670 --> 00:08:26.240
and just be the dumbest piece
of [bleep] anyone's ever...

00:08:26.240 --> 00:08:27.307
[ Laughter ]

00:08:27.307 --> 00:08:28.475
Like, literally, that serves --

00:08:28.475 --> 00:08:30.377
That's what everybody
in my family needs.

00:08:30.377 --> 00:08:32.579
They're like, look at this dummy
who doesn't understand anything.

00:08:32.579 --> 00:08:35.415
-I'm remembering a bit
from one of your specials

00:08:35.415 --> 00:08:37.684
also of when
you're playing a game

00:08:37.684 --> 00:08:40.554
and a -- and a part of a piece
of the game goes underneath.

00:08:40.554 --> 00:08:42.189
-They can't --
-A piece of furniture.

00:08:42.189 --> 00:08:43.557
-They can't keep dice
on the table.

00:08:43.557 --> 00:08:45.459
-Yeah.
-And so it's like your favorite

00:08:45.459 --> 00:08:47.427
moment is when you get to hide.
-Yeah.

00:08:47.427 --> 00:08:49.296
When I crawl under a couch
to find a dice,

00:08:49.296 --> 00:08:50.631
I just kind of stay there.

00:08:50.631 --> 00:08:52.766
-That really --
that really stuck with me.

00:08:52.766 --> 00:08:54.368
-It's really nice.
Trust me.

00:08:54.368 --> 00:08:55.636
Like, at some point,
you're like,

00:08:55.636 --> 00:08:56.870
this is the only place
you get to be where,

00:08:56.870 --> 00:08:58.739
like, nobody's like,
what's --

00:08:58.739 --> 00:09:00.340
'Cause I'm pretending
like I'm in service to them,

00:09:00.340 --> 00:09:03.510
but I'm really just resting.
-Yeah. [ Laughs ]

00:09:03.510 --> 00:09:05.312
-Do you have a specific,
like, old trait?

00:09:05.312 --> 00:09:07.014
Do you feel
like your friends would be like,

00:09:07.014 --> 00:09:09.016
this is -- this is
Elizabeth's most...?

00:09:09.016 --> 00:09:11.585
-Um, it's, I mean, I don't know
if it's a trait

00:09:11.585 --> 00:09:13.520
or if it's more of
just like a general embodiment.

00:09:13.520 --> 00:09:16.056
I was, with text,
I was doing a lot of periods

00:09:16.056 --> 00:09:18.125
at the end of sentences
until a friend told me

00:09:18.125 --> 00:09:20.561
that it's really aggressive.
[ Laughter ]

00:09:20.561 --> 00:09:23.130
-Have you --
I've also was told recently

00:09:23.130 --> 00:09:25.165
that emojis are now
an old person thing,

00:09:25.165 --> 00:09:28.569
and I was so psyched
that I finally got on board.

00:09:28.569 --> 00:09:30.204
-Yeah, I feel like
I'm still searching

00:09:30.204 --> 00:09:31.572
for ones that are clever.
-Yeah.

00:09:31.572 --> 00:09:33.307
Some really like -- like,
I don't know,

00:09:33.307 --> 00:09:36.176
I get excited to use
like the lightning bolt,

00:09:36.176 --> 00:09:40.647
you know, like pow is kind of
how I feel when I use it.

00:09:40.647 --> 00:09:43.217
-By the way,
it's -- it's so depressing

00:09:43.217 --> 00:09:47.454
that somebody who
was in "WandaVision,"

00:09:47.454 --> 00:09:49.456
who, like, literally did some
of the best, like,

00:09:49.456 --> 00:09:52.526
lightning bolt stuff
I've ever seen is like,

00:09:52.526 --> 00:09:54.261
"But have you ever
done it in a text?"

00:09:54.261 --> 00:09:56.330
[ Laughter ]

00:09:56.330 --> 00:09:57.931
-This is what I'm talking
about,

00:09:57.931 --> 00:09:59.967
about the 90-year-old
thing though.

00:09:59.967 --> 00:10:02.102
I was watching
so much Anne Meara when we were

00:10:02.102 --> 00:10:04.938
doing "Eternity," and I haven't
watched the documentary yet,

00:10:04.938 --> 00:10:09.409
and I was so invested in her and
Jerry Stiller's late night bits.

00:10:09.409 --> 00:10:12.212
And it was -- it was
so fulfilling to -- to use --

00:10:12.212 --> 00:10:15.082
use that as a reference point
for -- for my character

00:10:15.082 --> 00:10:16.350
and for Miles Teller's
character.

00:10:16.350 --> 00:10:18.151
-It is very nice.

00:10:18.151 --> 00:10:20.454
I mean, I will try
not to give anything away,

00:10:20.454 --> 00:10:23.590
but it is very lovely to watch
the two of you as actors.

00:10:23.590 --> 00:10:26.026
Obviously, we're very familiar
with like -- you are --

00:10:26.026 --> 00:10:28.295
You were playing old people
in young bodies,

00:10:28.295 --> 00:10:30.497
and you both do a wonderful job.
I really enjoyed it.

00:10:30.497 --> 00:10:32.799
-It is -- it's a
it's definitely,

00:10:32.799 --> 00:10:36.236
like, a cross-generational,
I think, viewing experience.

00:10:36.236 --> 00:10:40.874
It's, um, it's a -- it's a film
that's set in this afterlife,

00:10:40.874 --> 00:10:43.610
but it's a really
ordinary love story,

00:10:43.610 --> 00:10:46.880
um, about a couple
that's been married for 65 years

00:10:46.880 --> 00:10:48.849
and a woman who ends up
in the afterlife and --

00:10:48.849 --> 00:10:50.751
and discovers
that her -- her first husband,

00:10:50.751 --> 00:10:52.886
who died in the Korean War
is also there

00:10:52.886 --> 00:10:54.688
and has been waiting
for 67 years.

00:10:54.688 --> 00:10:58.692
And it's -- it's a heartfelt
and screwball sort of comedy.

00:10:58.692 --> 00:11:00.327
-It's a very nice time of year
for it to come out.

00:11:00.327 --> 00:11:01.762
-Yeah.
-It's always lovely to see you.

00:11:01.762 --> 00:11:02.996
Thank you so much
for being here.

00:11:02.996 --> 00:11:04.064
-Thank you for having me.
-I really appreciate it.

00:11:04.064 --> 00:11:05.966
You guys,
this is Elizabeth Olsen.

00:11:05.966 --> 00:11:07.234
-Everybody, "Eternity"
will be in theaters

00:11:07.234 --> 00:11:08.602
everywhere on Thanksgiving.
We'll be right back.

